[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Your readme might be the reason why nobody is using your project. And I know this sounds dramatic, but look at most GitHub repos. Cool project, interesting idea, and then the readme is just installation, getting started, API, license, no screenshot, no demo, no'

[00:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'clear explanation, no reason to care. So, in this video, I want to show you how to write a readme that people actually read. Main thing here is that you need to earn that attention. So,'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what you\'re seeing here is my own project called Textual Games, and unfortunately, it has a bad readme file. So, let\'s see why is it bad. First thing that we are seeing is the description'

[00:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'right here in the about section. And we can see that my description is only Textual Games AI, and that one is not saying anything about my project. We need here one or two simple and clear'

[00:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sentences to explain what is this project actually about. In my case, this is an old retro video game where you\'re playing your own story as a book, and AI is generating those levels. So, that one'

[01:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'just needs to be simplified. You can, of course, use AI for something like that. Other thing here is, and that one is a positive thing about this readme, you need here an actual link so people can'

[01:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'go and click from your repo and go directly into your project. And here we come to the main part. So, the first mistake here is thinking readme is a documentation first. It isn\'t. At the'

[01:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'top, your readme is a landing page. So, the visitor here is asking, "What is this? Is this for me? Does it solve a problem I have? Is it alive? Can I try it quickly?" And documentation matters,'

[01:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of course, but documentation comes after interest. If I do not understand the project, I will never reach your API reference. So, the top of your readme needs to sell the project clearly. Let\'s'

[01:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'now see an example of a good-looking GitHub repository. This is also a project of mine. It is called 8-bit-CN. It is basically an 8-bit version of Shadcn, and we can see a description'

[02:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here that is much better than the previous one. A set of retro-designed accessible components and the code distribution platform, open source, open code. This is basically copy-pasted from Shadcn just with this retro thing added'

[02:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in front of designs. And when we go here to the main thing, we can see totally different pattern for the readme file. First thing we have is a title. This one can be even bigger. Visually, this'

[02:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'readme is not maybe perfect, but it\'s following all the rules and the pattern that needs to be followed. Then, we have a description right under the title. We have a link, visit 8-bit-CN. That one'

[02:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can also be a badge right here. So, here we have a sponsor badge. These could be badges on going to show you the project where you can make beautiful badges after this one. And then, we have literally a screenshot of the landing'

[03:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'page. So, if we go to 8-bit-CN, we can see that this is literally a screenshot, even like a screenshot from the old version, and it is telling us everything that we need to know. This project is'

[03:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'attractive enough that you see all these 8-bit patterns and all the things. So, it is a good thing to put a screenshot directly inside of your readme file so'

[03:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'people know exactly what is this project about. And here, you got the attention, and if people love this kind of design, they\'re definitely going to click on'

[03:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this link right here. Then, we have here contributing guide. So, this is for all the contributors. So, here we have please read the contributing guide, which is leading to another file from the GitHub repo, and we have a usage'

[03:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'example. So, this is now the API part where we are adding the button. How are we using the Shadcn registry with pnpm dlx shadcn@latest add and then the button. And we have here a screenshot of'

[04:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that button. And then we have the license, open source program, star history, and then you can put basically whatever you like. It\'s not important what do you put like after this like'

[04:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'first 10 to 20 lines. This is the most important part of your readme file. And I\'m going to show you now one project that I hope is going to become a'

[04:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'standard for readme files. It is called Shield CN and it is fully open source and free. This is not some kind of commercial. And here you can create beautiful badges for your readme file.'

[04:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, here if I type in orgdev for example, I can generate badges for my own readme and you can see here it took everything from my GitHub profile and I can just use all these'

[04:55] [scene:talk]
